<task id="043" project="spaarkeai-compose-r1">
  <metadata>
    <title>Frontend — Create `ComposeToolbar.tsx` (Open-in-Word buttons via shared lib + dispatch-action)</title>
    <phase>Phase 4: Frontend — SpaarkeAi Compose Surface</phase>
    <status>not-started</status>
    <estimated-hours>6</estimated-hours>
    <tags>frontend, react, typescript, fluent-ui</tags>
    <rigor-hint>FULL</rigor-hint>
    <rigor-reason>Task tags include 'fluent-ui' (UI implementation per ADR-021)</rigor-reason>
    <parallel-group>F2</parallel-group>
    <parallel-safe>true</parallel-safe>
    <parallel-reason>Separate file from `ComposeEmptyState.tsx` (Task 044) — both can run in parallel group F2 after 032.</parallel-reason>
    <dependencies>032</dependencies>
    <blocks>042</blocks>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Create `ComposeToolbar.tsx` — the toolbar component that renders "Open in Word for Web" + "Open in Word Desktop" buttons (consuming `useDocumentActions` from the new `@spaarke/document-operations` shared lib, Task 032) plus a dispatch-action surface for the `compose-summarize` AI action. The toolbar wraps reusable Fluent v9 toolbar primitives; it does NOT own any DOCX state.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    Senior React/TypeScript developer fluent in Fluent UI v9 toolbar patterns, the SpaarkeAi shared-lib hook conventions, and the existing `GET /api/documents/{id}/open-links` endpoint shape.
  </role>

  <goal>
    `ComposeToolbar.tsx` renders Open-in-Word-Web + Open-in-Word-Desktop buttons (both invoke shared-lib hook → `/api/documents/{id}/open-links`) and a `compose-summarize` dispatch button. Build green; ui-test green; dark mode renders.
  </goal>

  <context>
    <background>
      FR-12 mandates both Open-in-Word buttons reuse `GET /api/documents/{id}/open-links` via the shared-lib `useDocumentActions` hook (extracted in Task 032). FR-19 + the broader Compose flow position the toolbar as the entry point for the `compose-summarize` dispatch (wired in Phase 6 smoke test). The toolbar does NOT own DOCX state; it is presentational + action-dispatch only.
    </background>
  </context>

  <constraints>
    <constraint source="ADR-021">Fluent UI v9 dark mode via semantic tokens — no hard-coded hex.</constraint>
    <constraint source="ADR-028">Auth scope acquired through `@spaarke/auth` only; no manual token handling.</constraint>
    <constraint source="project">REUSE `useDocumentActions` from `@spaarke/document-operations` (Task 032); do NOT call `/api/documents/.../open-links` directly.</constraint>
    <constraint source="project">No custom DOCX-feature integration outside TipTap OOB — toolbar buttons map only to OOB-supported actions.</constraint>
  </constraints>

  <justification>
    <existing>SemanticSearch's existing toolbar (with the SAME Open-in-Word buttons) is the reference UX. Task 032 extracts the underlying hook to the shared lib.</existing>
    <extension>No — Compose has a distinct toolbar (different action set: compose-summarize dispatch surface; different layout vs SemanticSearch grid). A separate component is needed; the shared lib provides the reusable hook.</extension>
    <cost-of-doing-nothing>FR-12 fails — Compose has no Open-in-Word entry points; users cannot escape to Word for advanced editing; Phase 6 smoke test cannot fire `compose-summarize` from the UI.</cost-of-doing-nothing>
  </justification>

  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>projects/spaarkeai-compose-r1/spec.md</file>
      <file>projects/spaarkeai-compose-r1/plan.md</file>
